This article discusses the executive orders issued by President Donald Trump on March 18, 2020, regarding healthcare and the response to the COVID-19 pandemic. The President declared a national emergency due to the threat posed by the novel coronavirus known as SARS-CoV-2. The order states that the healthcare system needs to be able to respond to the spread of COVID-19 and that all necessary health and medical resources, including personal protective equipment and ventilators, should be properly distributed. The Secretary of Health and Human Services is delegated the authority to require the performance of contracts or orders to promote national defense and to allocate materials, services, and facilities as necessary. The Secretary may also determine the nationwide priorities and allocation of health and medical resources and control their distribution in the civilian market. The Secretary is instructed to issue orders and adopt rules and regulations to implement the order. The order does not affect the authority of executive departments or agencies or the functions of the Director of the Office of Management and Budget. It is intended to be implemented consistent with applicable law and subject to the availability of appropriations and does not create any enforceable rights or benefits against the United States or any other party.